oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dc:description: By Ken Gould Union Leader Plymouth Reporter A new industrial plant, hardly a year old that is operating on a four shifts a day and a tremendous expansion in the educational facilities at Plymouth Teachers College is the good news for Plymouth located at the foothills of the White Mountains. The Sprague Electric Company that started operations in a brand new plant less than a year ago with about 60 employees, now has over 250 regularly employed, and is looking for more applications from women to turn out the solid tantalum capacitor that is used in missiles, radio, radar, television, photography and allied uses. $1 Million Budget Plymouth Teachers College that had an enrollment of 454 less than 4 years ago, predicts a student body of 905 this fall and 1305 just four years from now. Its budget for 1962-63is about one million dollars of which more than half, or about $650,000, go for personal services. It presently has 107 full-time employees. Newest addition to the facilities at the college is Blair Hall, a mens dormitory, that was occupied in 1960. It cost about $700,000 and houses 166 men. Ground breaking will be held in November for the construction of a dormitory for women that is estimated to cost $975,000. It is to the located on the property of the former Pemigewassett Hotel on Highland St. It is expected to be occupied in Sept. 1963. $60,000 Library Also in the fall of this year, ground is expected to be broken for the construction of a new library that will house 65,000 volumes. This is estimated to cost $600,000 and will be located on the front of the lot where the womans dormitory is to be build. Capital improvements planned in the next 10-year period include: a new science classroom building at a cost of $976,000; a six-room addition to Silver Hall to the north of the present building that will provide space for the physical education department and also rooms for the music and drama departments, at a cost of $189,060; an addition to the administration building at a cost of $52,000; a remodeling of the present library into classrooms and offices at a cost of $30,000; an extension of the athletic field by some 18 acres to the north plus equipment at a cost of $50,000; a housing group for married students comprising 30 units, at a cost of $360,000; a new mens dormitory to house 225, at a cost of $953,000; an athletic field dressing and storage building at a cost of $21,000; and a purchase of property from the Plymouth School District at a cost of $426,250. Also planned in the future is a swimming pool at Silver Hall at a cost of $260,000; and two more dormitories costing one million dollars each to house 225 men and women students respectively. oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dc:title: Oral history interview with Miss Olive Abbott
oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dc:creator: Blaine, Quentin
oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dc:description: Abbott speaks about teaching English at Pinkerton Academy from 1943-1967, when she became head librarian, a position she held through the date of the interview in 1980. Discusses the campus, budgeting, materials used for teaching, library purchasing, and student employment in the library, as well as student discipline and community leadership for the academy.
oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dc:subject: educating; interviews; media centers; schools; secondary education
oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dcterms:spatial: Derry (Rockingham county, New Hampshire : inhabited place)
oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dcterms:provenance: Michael J. Spinelli Jr. Center for University Archives and Special Collections, Plymouth State University, Plymouth, NH, USA
oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dc:description:
Olive Abbott Changes in English education in a public academy, growth of high school library.services and expansion of a public secondary school from 1943 to present as seen by a teacher, department head and school librarian. Miss Abbott began teaching in Bristol, N.H. in 1936. In 1943 she moved to Pinkerton Academy in Derry as teacher/ chairperson of the English Department in 1943. In 1967 she became head librarian. Describes growth of school from 250 to 2300 pupils Physical facilities and changes Equipment Curriculum Student services such as cafeteria, transportation,. organized recreation School organization Administration Supply procedures The World War II years Audio-visual materials Class size Mini courses Running a school library Use of pupil volunteers Marking systems Advising year books Social activities Changes in pupil behavior Relationships between community and school Vocational education Changes in teacherssalaries Teacher behavior and rewards of teaching Influencing youth
Oral History Interview with Miss Olive Abbott
January, 1980 Derry, NH
by Mr. Quentin Blaine
For the Oral History Center
INTR: This is an interview with Miss Olive Abbott by Quentin Blaine for the Plymouth State College History of Education in NH Program at Derry, NH, on January 12, 1980. INTR: Miss Abbott, you graduated from Plymouth State College in 1936? INTE: Yes.
INTR: And you taught at Bristol until 1943?
INTE: That's right.
INTR: What level of education did you teach?
INTE: Secondary.
INTR: Secondary as an English teacher?
INTE : Yes, when I came to the Academy, I was Head of the Department from 1943 until 1963. INTR: I see, you moved right into the Head of the Department. INTE: Y.
INTR: How many teachers were teaching in the department when you first started teaching?
INTE: Three.
INTR: How many students were at Pinkerton?
INTE: About two hundred and fifty students.
INTR: How many buildings belonged to Pinkerton, it's sort of a campus type set up.
INTE: Well, we had the original building which used to be called the Freshman Building, the Pinkerton Building, and the Haines House, and the Farm, and then the next addition to the Campus was the Library Building in 1959, and that was a great addition, then the first portable that became Room Number 60, which I think was there when you were a student.
INTR: Yes, just beginning.
INTE: One little portable, and then they added the Shepard Building and the two large portables and the English wing. The small house became the Guidance Department; the McKenzie House across the street became the Business Office, the Alumni Center and the Director of Athletics is over there now. It's a big Campus.
INTR: Now houses approximately two thousand students?
INTE: This year I think it was about nineteen hundred; two years ago we got up to twenty-three hundred students.
INTR: That was before Londonderry withdrew?
INTE: Yes.
INTR: When you first came to Pinkerton, were all the modern facilities in place as far as running water and toilets and everything? Was there a centralized bell and clock system then?
INTE: Yes it was. We didn't have a public address system; we had students who went about with notices. It was much easier than the public address system; but no, they were all modern facilities.
INTR: Were there lunch programs there?
INTE: Yes, there was a modified lunch program the first few years I was here; it was sandwiches, desserts, and milk, and it was in the Home Economics Department, which at that time, was on the main floor of the Old Freshman Building, which we call now the Old Academy Building, the Original Academy Building.
INTR: That's a wood-frame building?
INTE: Yes, the little one down at the foot of the driveway. Then, as the school became larger, we had a school lunch program at the Haynes House and on the first floor. That was a modified school lunch program. Then, of course, when the Shepard Building opened, the modern cafeteria was included and this year we've had an addition to the cafeteria; it's doubled in size and they have, of course, a much greater choice of meals. It is in connection, I think, with the Government program.
INTR: When did Pinkerton first start this Government program for lunches? Was this in existence when you first came to the school?
INTE: I don't think so. I think that the program was sponsored by the school. I dont know exactly when the Federal program was instituted; probably when the Shepard Building and the cafeteria opened. I never go to school lunches; so I dont know very much about it.
INTR: How about transportation when you first came to Pinkerton?
INTE: Well, there were school busses, of course, not the way we have them at the present. There was a bus from Derry and it came over in.the morning and picked the students up in the afternoon. I've heard the students say, back in those days, they had a dime a day and they could ride over for a nickel and ride home for a nickel. However, if they wanted to stop at Page's in town, which was the hang-out, it was a quick lunch place, and they could get sodas and ice cream, etc. They would have to decide whether they wished to ride or eat, and many of them walked, which is unheard of at the moment. Then, of course, some of the students had cars. Then, of course, we had Hampstead and then the other sending towns when Londonderry busses were used, and if you're up to school now between 1:15 and 2:15, there are busses everywhere for the students and you better not be around here at two o'clock. All the natives stay in because these busses roll down over the hill, and then, of course, so many students have their own cars; it's a real traffic jam around here.
INTR: To a lot of people, it's really a very congested area?
INTE: Yes, and to get them out of the way and by 2:15, there are very few around unless they're staying for sports or extra curricular activities.
INTR: Has the organized recreation at Pinkerton changed over the years since you've been there?
INTE: Oh yes, I wish I had the figures to tell you of the number of the students involved in the number of sporting events, the clubs, organizations of all kinds. There's something going on at that school from seven o'clock in the morning until late at night. It's just a beehive, and I guess that's the way a school should be; keep interested in all kinds of things. The number of teams, when you were there, were football, basketball, baseball probably, and some volley ball, and a few other class activities. Now we have soccer, very highly organized and successful soccer program. There's track, all kinds of things that I dont know too much about; and we have winter track conditioning so the kids are ready in the spring, not only for the boys but girls. We have an outstanding track program for girls. This fall they won the New England Meet and we have many girls who participate in marathons, not only Boston Marathons, but some of them have gone to that famous one in New York City. If a student wants to come to Pinkerton and wants to get involved, he can be busy twenty-seven hours a day. It makes me feel very bad when I hear students say, "Nothing to do," it really is too bad because there are so many things for them to do.
INTR: We'll move on to your teaching experiences. You spent twenty years as English teacher. Were you head of that department for that full twenty years?
INTE: Yes.
INTR: Were you supplied with the normal teaching materials, such as, blackboards, maps, globes?
INTE: Surely was. The marvelous thing about teaching at Pinkerton Academy is, if you need materials, if you use materials, if you want materials, you get them. Now I have friends who are in the Public Schools and they're telling me that their budgets are being cut drastically for the library and they have been told that they're not to order anything extra. I have a very ample budget, and I can use it anyway that I wish to better the library and it's always been that way.
INTR: Whats the process for requisitioning materials as a teacher and as a librarian? Were you given a budget as a teacher or head of the department for the materials?
INTE: Well, back when I first came here, we had sort of a loose structure of budgets. There always seemed to be money, but as we grew and became more complex and had a larger faculty, just for examples, one year when we went back we had three classes: Sophomores, Juniors, and Seniors. The town of Derry had a new Junior High and instead of having just the seventh and eighth grades, they added the ninth grade; so we were cut back to three years. There were eight members on the faculty that year; we had a majority of men on the faculty, and the ladies used to say on the faculty that we were always out-voted. We were all friends and we enjoyed it, but we used to say we could never institute anything because we were always out-voted and then we went up to twelve on the faculty. Now there are about one hundred and twenty members on the faculty and that does not include the administrators and the specialists. I have graduated from being Head of the English Department; I am now a specialist. Everybody has to have a title, and you can see why now we have to have budgets and every Department has a Department Head and the Department Head works with the people in the Department. They make up the budget, and then the Department Head finalizes, I hate that word, finalizes the budget. It is submitted to the Headmaster or Principal, Business Manager. We now have a Business Manager because a school of this size is big business. So then the budget is submitted to a Committee of Trustees, and finally there may be a time when you're asked to come to meet with the Business Manager, the Principal and the Committee from the Trustees, and then you are asked to justify some of the things in your budget. Now, I have never been asked to come to justify because my budget has always been accepted. This is big business, and you make out your requisition or purchase order. It goes to the Principal; he ok's it, initials it; then it is sent to the Business Office and then the materials are ordered and you receive a statement every two months or so giving you a run-down on how much you've spent of your budget and how much you have left, etc. It's done in a very business-like way.
INTR: How about normal teaching supplies for the teachers, say paper?
INTE: That's included in the Department budget; and then the school supplies paper and pencils, etc. I guess the paper probably comes out of the General Fund and they buy tons and tons of paper and it's distributed that way.
INTR: When you were a teacher, how much input did you have in choosing your own textbooks and workbooks?
INTE: One hundred percent.
INTR: How often could you change them? Whenever it was in the budget?
INTE: Whenever it was necessary. Whenever new material came out that was better than we'd have. I would discuss it with Mr. Hackler and it would be ordered. We didn't have to be screened by a School Board or anything of that sort.
INTR: Did you ever use workbooks in your class?
INTE: Yes, the English Department had workbooks; they had magazines, Scholastic Magazines, and there's a little magazine that comes out called Read and it has all sorts of up-to-date interesting articles. The school spends a tremendous amount of money on materials. They want the students to have the best, and I yet have to hear anyone say that they have been cut back on materials, and that is extraordinary.
INTR: Has there ever been a pinch say during World War II, or at other times?
INTE: Well, World War II, of course, I came in 1943, we didn't have the freedom and we couldn't spend the money. We didnt have that much money, but there was no feeling that you couldn't afford to have certain things. It's only been since the affluent sixties and seventies that people have been throwing money around. I'm sure we've wasted money these last few decades or so because the students had to have everything. I'm sure that all of the AV material helped them, but we also noticed that sometimes these kids have been lacking in the fundamentals.
INTR: Has there been a push in that at the Academy?
INTE: Pinkerton has always adhered to the classic education, learning the fundamentals. We have been criticized because we've been oldfashioned, we've had discipline, we've expected kids to learn things, and we have had frills; but we havent given over to the frills and our students who go on to college do very well. We've had students in the very best colleges and they have made it; and I think that we've been very fortunate that we havent followed all the schools because we don't have to pull in nearly so much as some of those other schools that are wondering now how they are going to teach kids to read, write and add two and two.
INTR: Did you use Educational TV at classes or is that used much at Pinkerton?
INTE: They have TV; they have a TV studio; they make tapes.
INTR: Video-taping and all?
INTE: Video-taping and all that sort of thing.
INTR: So Pinkerton has a full range of AV equipment; video-tapes and overhead projectors, etc.?
INTE: Yes, definitely, and another very nice thing, since we are a campus school, each department has its own AV material. Normally, in many of the schools here in N.H., you'd have a Media Center. I run a library and we have a Media man.
INTR: Is he connected with the library?
INTE: No, he is separate. There's a studio and a taping place in the library building, but not only that, each department, for example, the English Department, has its own Media; and they have tapes and records and films and record players and all because actually it saves time and saves money and saves wear and tear having those bits and pieces of equipment right at hand rather than dragging them from the Saltmarsh Building down to the English wing, and it's very good sense. Thats part of their budget and they requisition for the machines and also the materials that they want.
INTR: Does the library have any job cataloging, say the video-tape materials or cataloging films for the school, or are these brought in from other sources?
INTE: They're brought in from other sources. Each Department has its catalog. The Media Department has a catalog of all of the Departments.
INTR: So the Departments would keep track of their own TV materials?
INTE: Oh yes, they're responsible for keeping track of it and keeping it in good working order. However, if there are problems that they run into, the Media man will help them. The young fellow who does the work, John Barry, graduated from Plymouth. He's a very nice young fellow. He does a lot with the kids. They have a Media Association, a club, and they do taping and they do a lot of things.
INTR: Has there been much change in the class size at Pinkerton while youve been there?
INTE: No, then again, as in so many schools, so many schools packed kids in, thirty-five or so. They've tried to keep the maximum class at Pinkerton at thirty, and they try to keep it at twenty-five. Now that's very good.
INTR: Very good size.
INTE: Yes, I think the classes this year are smaller. There was a time when we had the twenty-three hundred students that they got up to thirty-one, thirty-two; but I know for a fact that the cutoff point has been thirty and we were crowded; but every single student in that school when we had twenty-two hundred or twenty-three hundred students had a homeroom desk and a book. Thats another thing they are very insistent on, every single student in the class has his own book.
INTR: Are most of the teachers still using the standard textbooks? I'd say with English it would be quite a bit in composition books.
INTE: There are so many mini-courses now, you don't start on page one in an English book and end up on page 539, the way we used to. There are all kinds of fascinating courses. There's one on sports and boys are particularly interested, and it's a half-year course and it takes all the aspects of sports and it really is a fascinating course. I'd like to take it myself. There's another teacher who has one on American humor, and I'm always buying books and materials for these different courses, and then last year, they started an advanced placement course in English. It was for a group of Seniors. There were ten, I believe who took it last year, and they did a great deal of research in the library, and each one, it was an individualized program, and they would come in perhaps three or four days a week, sometimes they would stay in their classroom; but I got to know them, and if Mrs. West were busy, they'd come in and I'd get them materials and I thoroughly enjoyed having them. They have another group this year, but the emphasis now is on doing more than the ten pages assigned in the book, and in the Social Studies Department, we have so much material in the library and we are basically a reference library and the greater part of my budget is spent on materials for the courses, and anytime there's a new course instituted, I am alerted and I work with the Head of the Department. I work with the teacher who's to set up the course or who has set up the course. Some of them work in the summer, and I'm there a couple, two or three weeks after school closes. They come and we work together; we order materials so that I know what's going on. They know what I have. I get what they want and then the assignments are given and they send me a form telling me such and such a date. There will be so many people involved in the assignment due on such and such a date, and if the teacher has any pet references, the teacher lists the references so that I am alerted. Then quite often, on Monday morning, I'm busy with these forms that have been sent in and I get all of these different assignment sheets. I get the materials set aside, label them, we have special places for them, and when the kids come in and say I'm looking for Mr. Tag's assignment, it's right there for them, and they do use the library.
INTR: How large is the library? It's the Saltmarsh Library?
INTE: Saltmarsh Library. We have about 17,000 volumes, which is good for a Secondary School Library. I use the State Library a great deal especially for the advanced courses and they have the inter-library loan which gives me access to all of the college libraries in the State.
And you have no idea how the kids are impressed, if I say this book came for you from Dartmouth College or the University, Keene, Plymouth, or Exeter. It's a marvelous system, because now with the price of books, it's difficult to justify buying a twenty dollar book thats going to be used by one of the students. If there's a demand when I borrow these books and I see how valuable they are, then they are on my list and I buy them.
INTR: Are there any other staff working at the library?
INTE : Yes, I have a very, very fine first assistant; she has taken over the cataloging and she has become an expert in cataloging. She is also a very fine person in dealing with the students, and I have one or two clerks from the CETA Program and I have been very fortunate because they have worked out fine and then I have one other assistant so I have three or four people there.
INTR: Are these full-time staff?
INTE: Well, three or four of these are and I have one teacher who comes in the last period of the day. She's an English teacher, and she's interested in the library and then we are open until four o'clock in the afternoon and that's extraordinary. I used to close about twothirty, but now we have so many bus students and several of the towns have an early bus which leaves at two o'clock and then they have a five o'clock bus that comes to collect the students who want to go to a meeting or practice sports so the Student Council asked if the library could be kept open later on or longer than 2:30 or 3:00, and I said yes if some people wished to work and keep it open. I didn't feel that I wanted to stay from quarter of seven until four o'clock every day and there were several that were willing to do it. I stay one day a week. Then we have a study hall that is open from four to five so that after the library is closed these students can go to the study hall, and it's warm and pleasant for them and it's supervised, they can wait for the five o'clock bus.
INTR: How many students can the library hold at one time?
INTE: One hundred and fifty, thats a little bit different than from when you were there. We've doubled the size and we have an informal reading area and we have easy chairs. I havent yet been able to tell or impress on the Principal that we should have some cushions and bean bag chairs. I love bean bag chairs and the Principal doesn't like bean bag chairs, but thats about our only point of difference. We don't see eye-to-eye on that, but I don't see if kids are reading, enjoying the reading, doing leisure reading, I don't see why they have to sit in a straight hard-back chair; and I very often will go by and look in the stacks and there'll be kids either sprawled out reading or leaning up against the stacks reading and that's perfectly all right. I think that's great; it is just as much of a learning experience for them as sitting up in a hard chair. But the Principal thinks I'm a little weird in that Department; but I think cushions, bean bag chairs, maybe someday I'll get them, but I doubt it.
INTR: Do you use student volunteers?
INTE: Yes, we have a very nice group of student volunteers. Mrs. Burnham, my first assistant, organizes them and gets them and teaches them and gets them proficient, and you know the nice thing about that student group. They are never the members of the National Honor Society or the top of the classes. They're the kids that come to school everyday, get lost in the mass of students, and this is the one time that they are singled out and they can do something for the school. They are valuable members of the school and we give them letters at the end of the year and we have a party for them and they're helpful, they're thoughtful, and I just think it's great.
INTR: About how many students do you use?
INTE: I would say that we probably do with thirty-five or forty students a year. Some of them come in two or three periods a day; they live in the library. They can always do something helpful and they'll come to my office and say, "Any errands?" I have a couple of boys who love to do errands and it gives them a freedom and they have a pass and it just gives them that little bit of recognition that kids need and kids dont get. So many of them get lost and I'm always so pleased when I have them, and as I said, they're not the top or they're not the National Honor people because they're so busy studying so they can get good marks. I don't find that they do nearly so much services as they should; they do in some areas. I shouldn't say that, but here are these kids, and Mrs. Wheeler in her office has a whole staff, kids that run their legs off all over the Campus. They're bright, shining moments of the day, it is excellent and they'll never be on the Honor Roll, but in twenty years if you go to a Class Reunion, they have made it and I think partly because someone has taken the time to give them a little bit of attention. Thats the whole trouble with a big school.
INTR: It is.
INTE: It really is. Last year we had a girl who had spent probably eight or ten years of her life at Crotched Mountain. She was able to walk some and she had aluminum walkers. They came over from the Special Education class and said this girl would love to work in the library and they said, I don't see how she can." One of the Special Education teachers said, "I dont know whether you would want her," and I said, well, "Why don't you let us be the judge. Let her come and work here and we'll see. She doesn't have to go over the Campus delivering slips. She can stay at the desk." And she came in and I never was so proud of the kids on the staff as when she first came in. We said that Nancy would be coming and we never said a word about being kind or thoughtful and there were some rather nice-looking young men on the staff and they'd come in and say, "Hi, Nancy? How are you today?" Well, she'd just beam. They were doing it just because they were kind and thoughtful, and at the end of the year, she got a letter for being on the library staff, and she was so proud and so pleased and her mother took the time to call us and tell us how much it meant to her, to her and to Nancy. Then my roof fell in because the mother broke Nancy's heart because she wasn't going to be at the Academy this year. She wouldn't be on the library staff. But you know, you do an awful lot of good for some of those kids, it's too bad you can't do more.
INTR: You do what you can.
INTE: It's just the same with the Aggie boys. Now when you were at school probably you heard kids say, "Oh, they're nothing but the Aggie kids." Well, I'll put my money on the Aggie kids any day of the week, and they are the ones if they are on a farm and they own a woodlot now, they're doing all right. When they have their special dinner, always get a special invitation because I'm kind to the Aggie boys; they're kind to me. Now one came the other day and asked me about getting some copies of Robert's Rules of Order, and he said it was for the FFA. They told me at the bookstore, if you sent in a requisition, they would give me a twenty percent discount. So I said, "All right, I'll make it out." The boy came back twice to thank me for doing that for the FFA, and I said, "Well, I'm looking forward to the FFA dinner, and I'll expect another scoop of ice cream. They always have it after the maple syrup season. We have a sap house now on the Campus and they make marvelous maple syrup; so they have a roast beef dinner and the dessert is vanilla ice cream with freshly made maple syrup and it's great.
INTR: Thats a good benefit.
INTE: Yes, thats one reason I'm good to the Aggie boys because I like to eat, but there's so many things you can do for kids if you only had time to do more. And the thing that breaks my heart at the end of the year, some kind that you've worked with but that you don't feel you've done too much for, but you've tried to help them. They come and thank you, thank you for all you've done for them. Some of the kids will give you the idea of well, I deserve it, why didn't you do more for me, but I'm talking too much.
INTR: Well, we'll get back on track a little bit. I was going to ask what mix of books you bought for your library. Do you have a special mix?
INTE: No, I don't have a special formula because I work on it, and it works out fine because at the end of the year, it evens out of the different Departments. Now we did an inventory recently, and I have a very good Science collection, but I feel that I must spend more money in the area of Science so I've been ordering books; that's the way we do it and it works out very well.
INTR: You keep mostly with the reference materials?
INTE: Right.
INTR: Do you choose fiction for the library?
INTE: Yes, we have fiction.
INTR: Whats your basis for choosing that?
INTE: We go heavy on the classics and the reading lists that English teachers send in. And, of course, our fiction section can't compete with the fiction the kids are carrying around in pocketbooks. It's very tame compared with that, but that's all right. And we have a very large collection of paperbacks because I feel that kids like paperbacks.
INTR: As a librarian do you have to work longer and put in time during the summers?
INTE: Yes, I work until the first of July generally, and then I have people who work during the summer; but this last summer I worked most of the summer. Some days I would just put in an hour or two; but I was around here all summer and we were doing an inventory and I had three people working for me and I would go up and we'd talk over what I wanted done and then I'd take off for the day; but I did stay until the first of July and then I am always back at least a week or so before school opens.
INTR: Is this part of your contract to work this amount of time. You're not on the 180 day contract?
INTE : No, I give more days than I get paid for, but thats all right.
INTR: Does the library have an opportunity to take the students on field trips?
INTE: No, we don't do anything in that area because the classes are having field trips, and, as I said, we are a social center of the school because we're having meets and all kinds of things in the library. Whenever theres a meeting to be held, Mr. Ek will call and say, "I'd like to reserve the library for such and such a day, such and such a time." I have a big calendar and I write everything down and now you have to get in ahead because other people are always saying, "We'd like a meeting," or "We'd like to have this or that." Then we also have some activity in connection with the town and I belong to the Delta Kappa Gamma group, which is an honorary society for women in Education. We always have one meeting a year at the library. I belong to the AAUW in Manchester and sometimes they come down here and the Vocational Education Department in the school has grown considerably since you were here and we have a work program, work study program. The students come to school and stay in school until noon and then leave to many businesses and to factories here in town and thats under the Head of the Vocational Education Department. They have an advisory committee, interested men who come to school once a month and have a meeting. Thats always held at the library. Any receptions or parties or anything of that sort always end up in the library.
INTR: Were you able to take the field trips as a teacher? Did you go at all?
INTE: Yes, I did, not to the extent that they do now, but whenever it was feasible.
INTR: Where would you go on a field trip?
INTE: Well, it would depend; we might go to the University to a play, or to a speaker. We might take the group to some other school for a yearbook conference. It just depended on the situation.
INTR: At Pinkerton the marking is A through D?
INTE: Right.
INTR: The cutoff point is seventy percent?
INTE: Right.
INTR: And that's a school rule?
INTE: That's a school rule.
INTR: Do you have other duties as a librarian, say as you might have had as a teacher?
INTE: No, the only thing extra that I do in connection with the student body is that I am the Business Manager of the yearbook. In other words, I keep the yearbook in the black which keeps me busy. I also work with several groups who would be sending out invitations. They come to the library; they supervise the writing, the sending out of invitations, Junior Prom. Then I'm a general source of information or misinformation anytime anybody wants to know anything about the Academy or any of the rules, etc. They always filter in and ask me what went on and what happened and they ask about social activities now. Monday morning I have a group of girls coming in to see about Junior Prom invitations; getting them taken care of. I'm a general source of information or misinformation. Not only for school activities, but for the Alumni. We have an Alumni Director who is new and has not worked with many of the people. He's a very fine person, but he really hasn't had that much experience; and so I'm the source of information for him. He's always coming in to see me, and as I told you before you started recording, I get all kinds of requests for information for members of the Alumni and Robert Frost, and Alan Shepard. I had a very interesting inquiry this fall from the Daniel Chester French Foundation in Washington, D.C., and Daniel Chester French designed the two bronze plaques on the Pinkerton Building. John Pinkerton, youve rubbed John Pinkerton's nose many times, and they are making a complete bibliography of all the art work that Daniel Chester French did and they had heard that there were two plaques here at the Academy; so I had the Alumni Secretary take the pictures of the plaques and I sent all of the information to Washington. Thats the general type of thing I'm dealing with all the time.
INTR: As a teacher, did you have other duties than normal classroom duties?
INTE: Yes, all kinds of things: the two class plays and the yearbook, the Letter Women, our class advisor several times; you name it.
INTR: Did you prepare most of your examinations?
INTE: Yes.
INTR: Were there any other State examinations or special examinations given to the students?
INTE: There would oftentimes be a State exam given in English and Math and some kind of Science. I used to use sometimes standard English exams put out by the National Council of Teachers of English just to see how they were measuring up.
INTR: There's been quite a change in the curriculum at Pinkerton over the years; I know it's wide ranging from Agriculture to Home Economics to the traditional College courses and Vocational Education. What are some of the changes that have come about in the curriculum since you've been at Pinkerton?
INTE: Well, I would say in the last ten years there's been a tremendous change because we now have many courses, instead of staying with one particular subject the whole year a student will take a mini-course or half a year and there's been a tremendous increase in the number of courses; and I think it's a good thing.
INTR: So they come up with a more specific course within the Department itself, a specific type?
INTE : Yes, and the Departments have a great deal of freedom in choosing the type of course that is going to be offered to the students, and certainly, if a student is taking a course in the History of Sports or American Humor, they're going to find something that will interest them or fascinate them.
INTR: Are the mini-courses coordinated by the Department Chairman?
INTE: Yes.
INTR: And do these courses have to be approved beyond the Department Chairman?
INTE: Yes, they're approved, I believe, by a Committee of the Trustees and the Administration.
INTR: Who's in charge of insuring attendance and discipline at the Academy?
INTE: We have an attendance officer, a young man, he's not the Assistant Principal, but he is in charge of the discipline and he has his office, he has two secretaries who keep track of the attendance and the discipline is taken care of first by the teacher. If the student does something that's of a serious nature, then the teacher reports it to the Department Head and the Department Head takes care of it and solves the problem; or if it's very serious, it is referred to the Discipline Officer and then he makes the decision unless the student is going to be suspended or expelled. Suspension would depend on how serious the offense was.
INTR: What would be considered a serious offense?
INTE: I really don't know too much about it because in the library we aren't concerned too much with it because the students who come in there are interested and working, and a lot of them like to come in there because it's quiet. I think about the most serious offense we have is somebody who wishes to forge a library pass which is rather silly because they can get them without any difficulty. I don't sign library passes now, but my Assistant does. It used to be very easy to copy my initials, and I hope they haven't gone on to the life of forgery. They may have, but I don't know about the current reason for being suspended, probably for being rude, I really don't know.
INTR: Is there a lot of smoking on Campus now?
INTE: Yes, not on Campus, now they have a smoking area as you go up the hill here at the parking area, and anybody who has a cigarette in the morning before he attends classes can stay over there until the bell rings. They don't condone smoking during the day.
INTR: It's not permissible?
INTE: No, there are no smoking rules for the students.
INTR: So, it's only before and after school?
INTE: Before and after school.
INTR: But they no longer suspend you for smoking when outside of the school?
INTE: No, I guess smoking has become accepted. I don't smoke, but a lot of people do; there are more kids smoking, I guess, than ever.
INTR: More women, too?
INTE: More women, yes, ridiculous; I don't see how they can afford it.
INTR: Well, Pinkerton has sort of a different governance than other schools. It's set up by a Board of Trustees and has no dealings with the towns, the towns pay tuition to the Board of Trustees?
INTE: Right, however, over the last few years, we've had a tremendous surge of people in the town who either think they know how to run a school better than the Trustees and the Administration or they hope they can run it better. They have come from a Public School situation and they've been able to either cajole or threaten the School Board. A few years ago, when they were getting ready to sign the new fifteen year contract with the sending towns, we had a very vocal group of people who were adamant that there should be control and people should be elected to the Board of Trustees from the towns. I don't know what they think happened because every single town has a representative on the Board of Trustees; but these people weren't the ones that the group wanted. We do now and I think it's a very good thing. They have an Advisory Committee, in other words, each town elects or sends two or three representatives from the town, not the Board of Trustees but representatives to come to the Trustee's meetings. They have no voting power, but at least they know what's going on. Now the Trustees were not putting anything over on the people. I don't know why these people decided that something underhanded was going on. Pinkerton has been solvent for years which is more than some towns can say. We've had a very fine combination of Educators and Businessmen on our Board of Trustees, and they have done an outstanding job and now these towns can have representatives come to the Trustee's meetings. Reports are sent back to the towns; I think it's fine because these people say, "We're spending our money, and we should know whats going on." We had a farout group who wanted to have people in charge of discipline, who are not even connected with the school. It was the most stupid thing I've ever heard of. You know how some of these people in town say, "Well that kid shouldnt be sent out of school, he has a perfect right, etc." It was just idiotic, but the first contract was defeated. It was not accepted by the towns and it was a blow; but the way it turned out, I'm sure it was much better because the Academy gave a little bit and the towns gave a little bit; and there was a much better feeling that each one understood better. When the second contract was submitted and they had the vote here in Derry, Derry was the worst town that gave the most trouble. The people at the Academy and the members of the Alumni got busy and we organized and we had a telephone campaign and we had the entire voting list of the town of Derry. We divided it up so that we had perhaps ten or twelve calls to make and we talked with people and we had such an out-pouring of admiration for the Academy that it was extremely heartwarming because the vote was like seven hundred and thirty for the contract to ninety to the mal-contents.
INTR: So, the second came much better?
INTE: Yes, and the second one was so decisive that we haven't ever heard from these other people since.
INTR: Well, maybe they do have a little hearing on the board and they know what is happening now, which makes a change.
INTE: Yes, they do and the whole atmosphere is very much better, and I said to one of the Trustees, "I just feel that it was worth all the agony we went through and it's made a better contract. It made a much better feeling."
INTR: Is there a large administration at Pinkerton? Have you any idea of the numbers? Theres at least one Principal and a couple of Vice Principals and secretaries?
INTE: I don't know, someone said the other day there were twelve secretaries. Then we have four or five Guidance people, and we have the Vocational Education group. We have the librarians. There are a lot of administrators.
INTR: Is there a Music Program there, too?
INTE: Oh yes.
INTR: Is it still going strong?
INTE: We have one man who is forte in band and that's what he does. We have another one whos very good in choral work and we also have just opened in the Shepard Building a new Music Room stadium type rehearsal hall. You should come up there sometime.
INTR: I've noticed the building going up. It's a pretty big addition.
INTE: Yes, well that's a new Vocational Education Building thats going up in the back and that is going to be open within a year and that's going to improve the situation because it's going to take all of the Vocational Education classes that are spread around. Theyll all be in one place.
INTR: Youll have the Shop right there, too?
INTE: Shop and the whole thing and it's going to be great.
INTR: When you first started teaching, was it in the day when you supplied your own housing, all your own housing costs?
INTE: Oh yes, when I first came here, there was Hildreth Hall, which belonged to the Academy. It was a big old three-story wooden building down here where the Field House is now and that was a very old and historic building. It had been an inn and a tavern when the Turnpike first started here, came up here in 1803, and that was owned by the Academy, but we paid board and room.
INTR: So you lived at Hildreth Hall?
INTE: I lived there and then in a couple of years I went into an apartment with one of the other teachers and then for a long time I've had my own apartment. Now this house is owned by the Academy and it's rented to the faculty.
INTR: I see. Is the Academy still buying up property or were these long ago acquisitions?
INTE: These were long ago acquisitions. This one, this house is called the Bingham House, and it was given to the Academy by George Washington Bingham, who was a Principal at the Academy in the early 1900's and the late 1890's. He left this to the Academy. The next house up is the Littell House and I believe the Academy bought that. Then they were left the Haynes House on the Campus, the big white Home Economics Building. They bought the small house which is on Pinkerton Street and that was the Guidance House, now they have new offices for the Guidance Department.
INTR: Was this the Principals house for awhile?
INTE: Yes, the Principal's house later was the little Mackenzie house across the way and that was left to the Academy by Mr. and Mrs. Malcolm Mackenzie and now that is the Business Office and the Alumni Director is down there and the Athletic Director has his office down there.
INTR: When you were at Hildreth House, did you have your private apartment or was it a rooming house?
INTE: It was the old fashioned rooming, board house.
INTR: You cooked your own meals?
INTE: No, there was a couple who ran it, they hired it from the Academy and it was run just like an old fashioned boarding house and we had our meals and our room.
INTE: I don't even remember; it's been so long ago. Probably, I wouldnt dare to guess, they were nominal you know.
INTR: They were geared to a teachers salary?
INTE: Yes, they were geared to our salaries.
INTR: Do you remember what your first salary was?
INTE: My first salary at Pinkerton was fifteen hundred dollars.
INTR: How does that compare now?
INTE: I don't know what the starting salary is, I don't know whether it's a high eight thousand or nine thousand, probably it's nine thousand.
INTR: Do you know the upper end of your salary section that you are in?
INTE: I don't know, we don't discuss salaries at Pinkerton, theres no salary schedule.
INTR: Each salary is negotiated individually?
INTE: Yes, negotiated, and if you are a valuable member of the faculty and if you do a lot of work for the Academy, you are paid.
INTE: No, you are given a contract and your salary is on it, and if you arent satisfied with it, you can go in and talk with the Principal; and if you can prove that you are worth more, you'll get more.
INTR: And so they give a tender offer, and you accept, reject it or compromise?
INTE: Yes, and if you add duties, if youre doing more work, you can go in and say, "Well now, I had thirty-five major social events in the library that I washed the coffee pots for," and so forth and so on. I haven't starved and I feel that I've been well paid.
INTR: Do you feel that a teacher has any community or church obligations, social obligations, now? Has it changed over the years?
INTE: Yes, I suppose so; I have never been in a situation. I know in some small towns a teacher was told she had to go to a certain church and she had to do this and that. I've never been in that situation and. now, of course, there are so few teachers that live here in this particular area. There are five of us right here across the street, the Burnhams, they own their own house. You can come and go as you want to; but I have lived here so long that I have become involved in community things and that is entirely up to the individual. If you want to be involved, o.k.; I can't live unless I'm involved.
INTR: Is there a community appraisal of your status as a teacher? Do you recognize that in the community?
INTE: Yes, I do, and when I go to Class Reunions, I get a very fine warm feeling.
INTR: Your position of being a teacher is recognized?
INTE: Right, and not too long ago I was at a Reunion and a boy, it was a man, came up to me. It was a twenty-fifth Reunion, and when this young man was in school, he was sometimes a bit fractious, and he said, "How does it feel to be one of the most admired women in the town of Derry?" And I said, "It feels very nice," and I said, "I appreciate it and I certainly appreciate the feeling and the rapport that I get from the people that I have worked with and the students that I've had." Now that means a lot. And this kid when he was at school, I didn't think he'd ever speak to me again; but he's grown up; he's become successful; and I thought that meant a lot to me to have him come and say that to me.
INTR: Well, I think we've covered quite a few of the extra-curricular activities that go on at Pinkerton, many of them that you've been involved in yourself. There is the question of promotion and commencement. How was promotion graded at Pinkerton? It's still passing a certain number of courses and then you move on into another year?
INTE: Yes.
INTR: And as soon as you reached a level, there would be credits?
INTE: So many credits, sixteen credits.
INTR: With so many required and so many not, you graduate?
INTE: Yes.
INTR: There is a large commencement at the Academy?
INTE: Yes, I hope they never change it because that commencement on the front lawn is a lovely event, with the Trustees coming out of the Pinkerton Building and Academic Procession and the class marching out. Now they have the school band that plays and the bell in the tower rings once for each year that the school has been in existence and it's up in the 165's or more now and it's just a very nice occasion. Some people have talked about having it up at the new athletic field, the Memorial Field, which is up in the back pasture. It's a lovely place, but I hope they never move it because it is a very moving experience. In the last few years, if the class has money enough, each girl will carry a red rose. If they don't have that much money, each girl will carry a red carnation, and they have their white gowns and the boys have the maroon gowns, but it's just a nice activity. There are a lot of things like that that have some class. It's a little bit different from the regular Public Schools. Now, of course, we go away for the Junior Prom. "Was your Prom here?"
INTR: Yes, it was at the school.
INTE: Well, now they go to the Wayfarer or someplace like that and they have a dinner and then the dance. So it is gratifying to be told, when you are there, that people like to have the Pinkerton students come because they're so well-behaved. Now last year all of the High Schools in Manchester were told that they would not be welcome at the Wayfarer because they had so much trouble with them; but we have no difficulty getting reservations at the nice places. I always say that you cant recognize the kids they're so dressed up and now the boys go in for top hats and capes and canes, and when you're dressed up, you act better and it's always a very nice occasion.
INTR: Well, we've pretty much covered the sheet. Have you anything else to add?
INTE: Oh no, I think I've talked too much.
INTR: Quite a bit this afternoon.
INTE: It doesn't bother me. Several years ago I went to Ireland to the Blarney Castle. I didn't kiss the Blarney Stone and I came home and I was telling my mother all the things I had done and I spoke about Blarney Castle. She said, "Did you kiss the Blarney Stone?" I said, "No, you have to lie down on your back and lean way over," and mother said, "I don't think you need it."
INTR: O.K., thank you very much for your time, Miss Abbott.
INTE: Well, you're very welcome. I think it's too bad, there are so many people in this town that should be interviewed and that's a project that the Alumni group is starting, a living history of the Academy.

oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dc:title: Background [Oral History of New Hampshire Schools Project]
oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dc:description: A written background of the Oral History of New Hampshire Schools Project, which ultimately produced 20 oral histories about the history ofeducation in the state of New Hampshire, recorded in 1978, 1979, and 1980. Included are why and how the project began, how it was funded, and operating procedures.
oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dc:subject: interviews; oral histories
oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dcterms:provenance: Michael J. Spinelli Jr. Center for University Archives and Special Collections, Plymouth State University, Plymouth, NH, USA
oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dc:description: Background In 1978 Dr. Christopher R. Clarke suggested that Plymouth set up an educational historical center which would collect, collate, and investigate the history of schools in New Hampshire following a prototype used in the State of Louisiana. After discussion an ad-visory council was set up consisting of Robert McDermand, William Taylor, Christopher Clarke, Archie Steenburgh, and Harold Hyde with Norton Bagley as coordinator. The Council, upon the advice of Mr. John Page of the New Hamp-shire Historical Society, decided that a starting place might be the conducting of oral history interviews with alumni and other persons who could tell about schools. A grant of $5,000 was generously made by the Plymouth State College Alumni Association to which the Class of 1963 at its reunion added the sum of $695.00. After researching the process of gathering oral histories, it was decided to get interviews from various time slots - people with the earliest experience in schools, the period after the first World War, the Depression, and the period since World War II. The neces-sary legal release forms were duplicated and a rough interview struc-ture was made. We wanted to know about physical facilities, equip-ment, teaching materials and methods, playgrounds and recreation, curriculum, administration, salaries and living costs, and attitude on the part of the public as to its expectation of teachers. All the interviews roughly follow these topics. However, it was soon found that the lead-primer type interview rather than a closed structure yielded most information. 2 Tape recorders and tapes were purchased and personnel sought for conducting the interviews. Dr. Bagley tried out the techniques with two alumni, Stephen Deshaies did one interview and Mr. Quentin Blaine, a History major at Plymouth, did the rest of the interviews. He tra-veled widely in the state and developed a fine interviewing technique. To him is due much of the success of the enterprise. we found that the most time-consuming and expensive part of the oral history pro-cess is the transcription and typing of the interviews. Mrs. Martha Anderson of Derry did many of the transcriptions, but the bulk of this task was done by Mrs. Marie Connelly, secretary to the Education De-partment. In addition to acquiring information about schools in New Hamp-shire, some information was acquired about the history of Plymouth Normal School. The synopses (see below) list any anecdotes about Plymouth and one entire interview with Nina Perkins Taylor describes Plymouth when Dr. Klock was principal. Dr. Bagley did extensive tapes on the Plymouth of the late 30's under Dr. Silver. The final folders on each interview contain the following in-formation: Copy of the tapes Legal releases Brief biography of the interviewee The text of the interview A synopsis of the interview After some experimentation, it was found that because of the length of the interviews (usually under 50 pages) and the use of the lead-primer technique indexing of interviews would not facilitate 3 their use. Instead a synopsis was done informing the researcher in a few sentences the major thrust of the interview and then a listing of some of the topics covered was made. This listing usually follows consecutively the text of the interview. A file of the oral history folders will be found in the Rare Books section of the library and a similar file is located in the Education Department. While the plan to get successive slices of time spans in teach-ing in New Hampshire schools was successful, more information was ob-tained in terms of perspective because especially people who began teaching in earlier years either continued to teach until retirement or re-entered teaching later on. These people give a contrast between teaching in the early days and the period of World War II and after. If taken beside the interviews of people entering teaching in the 60's and 70's, such interviews tell much about changes in the schools and changing teacher, administrative pupil and parental attitudes. The researcher is advised not only to use the tape transcriptions, but to listen to the tapes as well. Much of the quality of what a per-son says can only be gained from voice inflection and other non-lan-guage types of communication. It is hoped that in the future, when funds may be more readily obtainable that Dr. Clarke's original idea of setting up a state his-torical educational institute can be completed. Until such time, Ply-mouth does have a collection of taped interviews which constitute pri-mary sources for the history of New Hampshire schools. 4 Operating Procedures ADVISORY COUNCIL The Council should be small and should include at least one person familiar with the subject of the investigation. In general, it should be an advisor as to such matters of policy as: 1. Objectives of program. Definition of scope. 2. Procedures for program. Criteria for selection of interviewers and interviewees. 3. Procedures for financial, institutional and legal controls. 4. Policy as to use of materials (ownership, access for scholarly research, access for class use, access for general use). DIRECTOR Director should be chosen by Advisory Council. Director is charged with carrying out the policies set by Advisory Council. INTERVIEWEES The Council may wish to set some guide lines for selection of interviewees. One plan might be to divide the state into urban (Portsmouth, Manchester), town (Derry, Plymouth) and rural (Stark, Groton) and begin by interviewing an elementary and secondary teacher and an administrator from each group, making 9 interviews for the first semester. Aside from people who may volunteer for interviews, the Council should probably select interviewees from persons known to the Coun-cil who would fit into one of the following groups: 1. Persons without whose input the objectives cannot be ade-quately carried out. 2. Persons who would make unique and significant but somewhat specialized contributions. 3. Persons who would make marginal but interesting contributions. 4. Persons who may be suggested as potential interviewees, but whose contributory value is probably low or unknown. INTERVIEWERS Interviewers should be selected by the Council and/or Director who will relate well to interviewees in terms of knowledge of subject to be explored, dress, language, expertise in phrasing questions and in steering interviews so that the pertinent subjects are covered. Interviewers should be trained in interview techniques by the Dir-ector or other persons with some background in interviewing. 5 LEGAL CONTROLS 1. Signed letter agreeing to interview. This letter explains the purposes of the research, the uses the material will be put to, time and place of interview. The letter as sent and the return of the confirmation letter or card have a certain standing in law as a contract. This letter and confirmation should be in file even if arrangements for the interview were made by phone. There should be an interviewer agreement for each interview; releasing the rights of the interviewer to information in the tapes. 2. Transcript of the interview is sent to the interviewee. There should be a signed acknowledgement of receipt. When the trans-cript is returned for further typing, a record should be made by the Director of receipt and date. When the finished trans-cript is sent to the interviewee, there should be a further written acknowledgement. BIOGRAPHICAL DATA SHEET FOR INTERVIEWEES A brief biographical data sheet should be filled out by the inter-viewee at the time of the interview and returned to the Director by the interviewer. This sheet should sufficiently identify the interviewee so that future researchers may evaluate data in the light of the interviewee's qualifications. INTERVIEW GUIDES An interview guide should be prepared by the interviewer and ap-proved by the Director. This guide may consist of a list of in-formation one wishes to elicit from the interviewee. The guide may be furnished the interviewee prior to the interview if the inter-viewee wishes. The sources seem to indicate that it is better to let the interviewee talk and for the interviewer to check the items which the interviewee covers on the guide. Items not covered in the free response of the interviewee can then be specifically asked. There seems to be no set "best" interview guide of procedure. If the guide is too specific, the spontaneity and the human interest anecdote is lost. If the guide is too loose, one may not get the historical information desired. The best procedure seems to be as described in paragraph one coupled with the interviewer's interrup-tion of the interviewee if a point is not clear, to make sure of names and places, or to get the interviewee back on track if there is excessive rambling. PROCEDURAL CHECK Council decides on state-wide plan for getting interviews. 6 Council sets policy for selection of interviewees and interviewers. Interviewers and interviewees selected. Interview guides developed. Training session for interviewers. Setting up interviews, followed by confirmation letters and replies. Interviews conducted. Biographical data collected. Interviews transcribed. Transcription of interview reviewed for accuracy. Transcription sent to interviewee. Interviewee returns transcription (another meeting by interviewee and interviewer may be necessary) . Edited transcription read by other persons. Final transcription typed and proofread. 7 Synopses of Oral Interviews Each interview has been analyzed as to its main points. These are presented for each interview so that a quick perusal can inform the reader if the material which is being researched will be found in the interview. A quick summary statement is given at the beginning of each synopsis which should also assist in discovering if the interview may have pertinent material for the researcher. Since all the interviews are relatively short to hear or to read the transcription, they should be readily usable. While in general the synopses follow the order in which the interviewee discusses a given topic, there are many returns to top-ics earlier mentioned and some repetitions as a result of the inter-viewing process.
Oral History of New Hampshire Schools Project

oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dc:subject: students; dance

oai_qdc:qualifieddc.dc:description: Plymouth State College's Contemporary Dance Ensemble was filmed by ESPN Wednesday as part of the opening ceremonies for the World Cup ski races at Waterville Valley. "It was funny because we danced in the snow in sneakers," said Chrissy Gaglio, a Plymouth State senior and CDE member. "It was sort of like running in the sand. But it was fun." Nine student dancers performed an original work, "Rhythm and Lines," coreographed by Cle Douglas to musical accompaniment by John Faddis. The CDE's dance was followed by a performance of the Waterville Valley Ski Ballet team and other festivities. Joan Wiegers is artistic director of the Contemporary Dance Ensemble.
